  "opinion": "As a woman with a PhD in science who grew up in a household where my father was a university professor and my mother had no formal education, I've witnessed firsthand how systemic barriers shape opportunities. The gender gap in science isn't just about numbers—it's about the quiet moments when a female student feels unseen in a lecture hall, when a researcher's ideas are dismissed as 'too speculative,' or when women in STEM fields are the first to be labeled 'unstable' during career transitions. I've seen this play out in my own work as a part-time professor in Kansas City, where many of my students are from backgrounds where their families didn't emphasize STEM careers. The gap exists because of deeply embedded cultural narratives that equate science with masculinity, even though I've seen how my own mother's resilience in navigating life without formal education taught me the value of perseverance. Addressing this gap isn't about 'fixing' women—it's about dismantling the structures that make science feel inaccessible to those who don't fit the traditional mold. For me, it means creating spaces where vulnerability is valued, where mentorship isn't just about technical skills but also emotional safety. I've found that when students feel seen, they're more likely to persist. In my teaching, I intentionally include diverse role models who challenge the narrative that science is a solitary, male-dominated pursuit. The work isn't easy—it requires acknowledging the emotional labor of being a woman in academia while also navigating my own depression and the complexities of being an immigrant-raised person in a field that often feels disconnected from lived experiences. But it's worth it. When a student from a marginalized background tells me they're finally feeling like they belong in science, that's the moment I know we're making progress.",
